<subSubSection id="7BFFEAD3FFF3A7070CB0FA38FDCEA722" lastPageId="61" lastPageNumber="62" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="description">
<paragraph id="335AB958FFF3A7060CB0FA38FABFA167" blockId="60.[151,1436,1384,1994]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060CB0FA38FEE9A3BE" bold="true" box="[199,344,1462,1488]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Description</emphasis>
. Orbit without additional setulae behind level of upper orbital bristle. Arista short- to medium-pubescent (as in 
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFF3A7060DB8FA53FDF4A399" box="[463,581,1501,1527]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–6" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1156,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1123]" captionTargetId="figure-376@7.[151,1436,194,1132]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 2–6. Leptocera heads and antennae. Heads of (2) L. argentinica sp.n. (Argentina); (3) L. fulva (Costa Rica). Arista and first flagellomeres of (4) L. aequilimbata (Peru); (5) L. neocurvinervis (Chile); (6) L. caenosa (U.S.A.). ad s—additional setulae on orbit, l or—lower orbital bristle, u or—upper orbital bristle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311872/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 4, 5</figureCitation>
). Palpus slender. Scutum with two pairs of greatly enlarged presutural acrostichals (
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFF3A7060D45F98AFE2BA070" box="[306,410,1540,1566]" captionStart="FIGURE 109" captionStartId="61.[151,255,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,390,1294]" captionTargetId="figure-283@61.[151,1436,390,1294]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 109. Leptocera parallelipennis sp.n., holotype male (Juan Fernández Is.). ac—enlarged acrostichal bristles, dc—dorsocentral bristles, m—marginal bristles, phu—posthumeral bristle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311906" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311906/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 109</figureCitation>
: ac). Wing usually greatly reduced, extending slightly beyond level of tip of scutellum (
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFF3A7060CE8F9A4FE86A02A" box="[159,311,1578,1604]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–15" captionStartId="10.[151,269,1628,1652]" captionTargetBox="[163,1413,194,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-176@10.[148,1433,194,1605]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 10–15. Leptocera wings: (10) L. fulva (Belize); (11–12) L. ellipsipennis, showing variation (Juan Fernández Is.); (13) L. cultellipennis (Juan Fernández Is.); (14) L. parallelipennis sp.n., normal wing venation (Juan Fernández Is.); (15) ditto, aberrant venation. Scale bar 0.1 mm. Cs—costal sector." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311876" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311876/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs. 11–15</figureCitation>
; except in 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFF3A7060DA3F9A5FDDDA02A" authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1955" box="[468,620,1579,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duplicata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060DA3F9A5FDDDA02A" box="[468,620,1579,1604]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">L. duplicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), strongly infuscated. R 
<subScript id="AF61BB1DFFF3A7060FD1F9B4FC71A026" attach="left" box="[934,960,1594,1608]" fontSize="6" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">4+5</subScript>
only slightly curved forward in the macropterous 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFF3A7060D49F9DAFE7DA003" authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1955" box="[318,460,1620,1645]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duplicata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060D49F9DAFE7DA003" box="[318,460,1620,1645]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">L. duplicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Fore tarsus not sexually dimorphic. Main bristles of mid tibia unusually long and strong (
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFF3A7060C87F9F4FEF7A0FA" box="[240,326,1658,1684]" captionStart="FIGURES 16–29" captionStartId="12.[151,269,1761,1785]" captionTargetBox="[278,1316,187,1725]" captionTargetId="figure-148@12.[276,1320,183,1735]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 16–29. Leptocera mid tibiae and basitarsi. Mid tibia, dorsal: (16) L. neocurvinervis (Chile); (17) L. duplicata (Juan Fernández Is.). Apical half of mid tibia and basitarsus, posterior: (18) L. parallelipennis sp.n. (Juan Fernández Is.); (19) L. ellipsipennis (Juan Fernández Is.); (20) L. erythrocera (Honduras); (21) L. sphaerotheca sp.n. (Mexico); (22) L. plax sp.n. (Ecuador); (23) L. tapanti sp.n. (Costa Rica); (24) L. cymatonota sp.n. (Mexico); (25) L. parafinalis (Canada); (26) L. neofinalis sp.n. (Canada); (27) L. kanata sp.n. (Canada); (28) L. fontinalis (France); (29) L. nigra (South Africa). d ad—distal anterodorsal bristle, d d—distal dorsal bristle, d pa—dorsal posteroapical bristle, l ad—lowermost bristle of proximal anterodorsal series, l pd—lowermost bristle of proximal posterodorsal series, mv—midventral bristle, pa v—preapical ventral bristle, vb—ventrobasal bristle of basitarsus, v pa—ventral posteroapical bristle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311878/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
), with four proximal posterodorsal bristles (instead of the usual 2–3), lowermost bristle shifted distally (very slightly so in 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFF3A7060D97F92FFD2FA0D4" baseAuthorityName="Enderlein" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[480,670,1697,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cultellipennis">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060D97F92FFD2FA0D4" box="[480,670,1697,1722]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">L. cultellipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), inserted at or just below middle of tibia. Micropterous species differ from 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFF3A7060D68F946FE1FA08F" authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1955" box="[287,430,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duplicata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060D68F946FE1FA08F" box="[287,430,1736,1761]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">L. duplicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as follows: Knob of halter reduced. Syntergite 1+2 lacking the usual pale anterobasal area (only visible when abdomen is cleared). Bristles at posterior margin of tergites 2–5 enlarged.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFF3A7060CB0F89BFCCEA112" blockId="60.[151,1436,1384,1994]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Male terminalia: Sternite 5 with small pale area in front of posteromedial field of microtrichia; hind margin lacking enlarged scales (e.g., 
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFF3A7060E24F8B2FD08A138" box="[595,697,1852,1878]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–116" captionStartId="62.[151,271,1939,1963]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,268,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-80@62.[151,1436,263,1929]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 110–116. Leptocera cultellipennis (Juan Fernández Is.). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (110) lateral; (111) posterior; (112) ventral; (113) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (114) dorsal; (115) spermathecae; (116) ventral. lp—lamellate process of cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311908" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311908/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 113</figureCitation>
; except in 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFF3A7060F4AF8B2FC43A13B" authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1955" box="[829,1010,1852,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ellipsipennis">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060F4AF8B2FC43A13B" box="[829,1010,1852,1877]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">L. ellipsipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Epandrium with few long bristles ventrally. Posterior section of surstylus without process at base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFF3A7060CB0F807FB15A1CD" blockId="60.[151,1436,1384,1994]" box="[199,1188,1929,1955]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Female terminalia: Spermatheca elongate with dilated apical portion (e.g., 
<figureCitation id="ABDEA5DDFFF3A7060845F807FB26A1CD" box="[1074,1175,1929,1955]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–116" captionStartId="62.[151,271,1939,1963]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,268,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-80@62.[151,1436,263,1929]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 110–116. Leptocera cultellipennis (Juan Fernández Is.). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (110) lateral; (111) posterior; (112) ventral; (113) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (114) dorsal; (115) spermathecae; (116) ventral. lp—lamellate process of cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5311908" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5311908/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 115</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFF3A7060CB0F83EFAE7A1A4" blockId="60.[151,1436,1384,1994]" box="[199,1366,1968,1994]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF3A7060CB0F83EFEC2A1A4" bold="true" box="[199,371,1968,1994]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Biogeography</emphasis>
. This group of species is endemic to Robinson Crusoe I. (Juan Fernández Is., 
<collectingCountry id="4BF2F9C8FFF3A7060972F83EFAFBA1A4" box="[1285,1354,1968,1994]" name="Chile" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Chile</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="335AB958FFF2A7070CB0FF19FDCEA722" blockId="61.[151,1436,151,332]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF2A7070CB0FF19FEF6A6DF" bold="true" box="[199,327,151,177]" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">Phylogeny</emphasis>
. The 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFF2A7070DE7FF16FDE1A6DF" baseAuthorityName="Enderlein" baseAuthorityYear="1938" box="[400,592,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="61" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cultellipennis">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFF2A7070DE7FF16FDE1A6DF" box="[400,592,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="61" pageNumber="62">L. cultellipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup is clearly monophyletic as evidenced by the autapomorphic mid tibia chaetotaxy (lowermost bristle of proximal posterodorsal series shifted distally) and two pairs of greatly enlarged acrostichal bristles. The lack of orbital setulae behind the upper orbital bristle is probably also apomorphic (reversal to ancestral state), since the closest relatives of this species group on the South American mainland all have such setulae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
